    centralQuestion: 'How can inquiry reconstruct habits and institutions when inherited responses no longer solve shared problems?',
    lead: 'John Dewey recast knowledge as an activity within changing environments. Influenced by Darwin and the emerging human sciences, he rejected the picture of a spectator mind trying to copy a finished world. Inquiry begins when ordinary habits are disrupted by an indeterminate situation; observation, hypothesis, experiment, and revision transform that situation into one whose parts can be understood and acted upon. Ideas are instruments in this process, but instrumentalism does not mean that whatever feels useful becomes true. Claims earn warranted assertibility through methods answerable to evidence and future correction. Dewey extended this experimental outlook to education, ethics, art, and democratic life. Schools should organize growth through guided participation rather than passive recitation, and democracy is a mode of associated living sustained by communication as well as a set of voting rules. His faith in social intelligence faced industrial inequality, racial exclusion, imperial conflict, and the limits of reform. The exhibit places Dewey between Peirce’s logic of inquiry and later theories of public reason while keeping the contested politics of his applications in view.',
