    lead: 'Rudolf Carnap brought formal construction to the philosophical ambitions of the Vienna Circle. In The Logical Structure of the World, he explored whether knowledge could be rationally reconstructed from an austere basis through explicitly defined relations. He later shifted from construction to the logical syntax of languages, arguing through the principle of tolerance that philosophers may design different formal frameworks for different purposes if their rules are stated clearly. Work on semantics, modality, probability, and confirmation followed after his emigration from Nazi Europe to the United States. Carnap’s criticisms of metaphysics are often reduced to a slogan that every metaphysical sentence is nonsense. His actual positions changed, and his mature distinction between internal questions asked within a framework and external practical questions about adopting one leaves room for plural conceptual tools without turning framework choice into arbitrary taste. Quine challenged the analytic–synthetic distinction on which much of this program relied, while Popper contested verificationist pictures of science. The exhibit presents Carnap as a constructive engineer of languages, not merely a censor of forbidden sentences.',
