    centralQuestion: 'How can inquiry remain rational when no finite body of positive evidence can finally verify a universal theory?',
    lead: 'Karl Popper made criticism, not verification, the center of scientific rationality. Responding to the problem of induction and to debates around the Vienna Circle, he argued that universal theories cannot be conclusively confirmed by accumulating favorable instances, but they can expose themselves to potential refutation through risky predictions. Falsifiability therefore marks a methodological boundary between empirically testable science and claims insulated from possible failure. It is not a command to discard a theory at the first awkward datum: observations are fallible, tests rely on auxiliary assumptions, and scientists must judge whether adjustments are independently defensible. Popper described knowledge as conjectural and emphasized severe tests, corroboration, and error elimination. The same critical ethos informed his attack on historicism and defense of an open society in which institutions permit peaceful correction of rulers and policies. He was friendly with some logical empiricists but was not a member of the Vienna Circle, and his sharp retrospective accounts of their differences should not be accepted uncritically. The exhibit makes falsification a demanding practice of vulnerability to evidence rather than a classroom slogan.',
